## What happened

In .NET 11, **DSA was removed from macOS**. Calling `DSA.Create()` (and any DSA signing/verification) now **throws at runtime** on macOS. Windows and Linux are unaffected.

## How to fix it

Since you need to **verify legacy DSA signatures**, you can't simply switch the signing algorithm — those existing signatures are DSA. Your options:

1. **Skip macOS for DSA verification** — gate the DSA code with a runtime check:
   ```csharp
   if (!OperatingSystem.IsMacOS())
   {
       using var dsa = DSA.Create();
       // verify signature...
   }
   ```

2. **Use a cross-platform crypto library** — e.g., [Bouncy Castle](https://www.nuget.org/packages/BouncyCastle.Cryptography) provides a managed DSA implementation that doesn't depend on the OS:
   ```csharp
   // Works on all platforms including macOS on .NET 11
   var dsaParams = DsaPublicKeyParameters(...);
   var signer = SignerUtilities.GetSigner("SHA256withDSA");
   signer.Init(false, dsaParams);
   signer.BlockUpdate(data, 0, data.Length);
   bool valid = signer.VerifySignature(signature);
   ```

3. **Restrict macOS builds** — if macOS support isn't critical, exclude it from your target platforms.

**Recommendation:** If you must verify legacy DSA signatures on all three platforms, **Bouncy Castle** is the most practical path — it gives you a pure managed DSA implementation that works everywhere regardless of OS-level crypto support.
